SIMPLE: agaric
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Agaric
<hw>Ag"a*ric</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>agaricum</ets>, Gr. <?/, said to be fr. <ets>Agara</ets>, a town in
Sarmatia.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A fungus of the
genus <gen>Agaricus</gen>, of many species, of which the common mushroom
is an example.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An old name for several species of
<gen>Polyporus</gen>, corky fungi growing on decaying wood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>female agaric</xex>⟦rdquo⟧
(<spn>Polyporus officinalis</spn>) was renowned as a cathartic; the
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>male agaric</xex>⟦rdquo⟧ (<spn>Polyporus igniarius</spn>) is
used for preparing touchwood, called punk or German tinder.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Agaric mineral</b></col>, <cd>a light, chalky deposit of
carbonate of lime, sometimes called <altname>rock milk</altname>, formed
in caverns or fissures of limestone.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Agasp</ent>⟦br⟧
